Mr. Louis R. Belmonte, P.E., District Traffic Engineer
As per your assignment, KMJ Consulting, Inc. has reviewed the request by Cheltenham Township to remove the
traffic signal at the subject intersection. PennDOT Publication 46 Chapter 4.10 was used as a general guide as
well as the PennDOT Form TE-151. As directed in Publication 46, the FHWA Implementation Package IP-80-12,
User Guide for Removal of Not Needed Traffic Signals, dated June 1980, was also used to evaluate the request.
This analysis looks at two proposed conditions, an all-way stop and stop signs only on Sycamore Lane. As
described starting on page 13 of the FHWA Guide, a Preliminary Screening reveals the following:
Sight distances were measured using criteria from PA Title 67, Chapter 441. The speed limits for both the major
road (Willow Avenue) and the minor road (Sycamore Avenue) are 25 MPH. Table 1 summarizes the results of
Safe Sight Distance, defined in PennDOT Title 67, Chapter 441.8(h).1
120 East Lancaster Avenue, Suite 105, Ardmore, PA 19003 p: 610.896.1996
As presented in Table 1, the existing intersection does not meet the required sight distance for the minor road
(Sycamore Avenue) approaches. An all-way stop will satisfy this sight distance requirement.
No major traffic generators that create sharp peaks in volumes are located at the intersection. The LaMott
Community Center/Free Library along with a playground is located on the NW corner. The low traffic volume
and proposed all-way stop would facilitate safe pedestrian use at the intersection.
Manual turning movement counts were conducted at the intersection on June 7, 2012 from 7:00 AM to 6:00 PM.
The volumes do not meet any of the MUTCD warrants for a traffic signal. A copy of the counts and warrant

believes that the original installation was related to a grammar school that existed at the corner, but has since been
No crash data is available for the time period before the traffic signal installation to allow comparison.
The FHWA Guide questions if accident problems were significantly worse after the traffic signal installation, and
if so, have alternative safety improvements been fully considered. As described in consideration 5, no crash data
is available for the time period before the traffic signal installation to allow comparison.

The Guide also notes that the volumes at the intersection should be relatively low (less than 800 entering during
the peak hour) and relatively balanced (ratio of major street volume to side street volume is less than 3:1). The
peak hour (4:30 PM to 5:30 PM) entering volume is 269 vehicles. The ratio of major street volume to side street
Currently, the intersection operates as a fixed time two-phase traffic signal (60 second cycle lengths timed in the
field). The intersection layout and operation is different than the traffic signal permit plan (Permit #3301) as there
was recent work at the intersection which included bulb outs and curb ramps. Given the consistently low volumes
at the intersection, an all-way stop should reduce delay by allowing vehicles to proceed after coming to a
complete stop instead of waiting for the signal to change. An analysis of the intersection using Synchro software
is presented in Table 2. The intersection was analyzed with the existing signal, proposed as an all-way stop and as
a two-way stop (stop signs on Sycamore Avenue).

As presented in Table 2, the overall level of service for the existing signalized condition is LOS A for the AM
peak and LOS B for the Midday and PM peaks. However, the all-way stop option shows all approaches during all
peaks as LOS A. The existing signal and two-way stop option show some approaches with a LOS B.
Michael Fleming, Public Works Coordinator for Cheltenham Township, Montgomery County, PA was contacted
in regards to an estimate for an annual cost savings after the removal of the signal. He mentioned that the average
annual electric cost per signal in the township is approximately $447 while the average cost for signal
maintenance is $766 per signal. Assuming a 15-year analysis period and interest rate of 12% (as shown in the
FHWA Guide) the equivalent savings is more in the range of $815 per year, as presented in the attached analysis.
This talk was not a part of our scope of work for the given assignment.
KMJ will defer to the Department for the final decision on whether the removal request should be approved.
